.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-02-28-cross-plan-test-count-not-updated.md:41:verification: "{}"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-02-28-cross-plan-test-count-not-updated.md:57:The feature count assertion is a brittle test pattern: any time a feature is added to feature-manifest.json, this test will fail for any subsequent plan that runs npm test. The root cause is that the test captures a point-in-time count rather than testing structural properties (e.g., "all features have required fields"). Plans that add features should include updating related count assertions, or the assertion should be refactored to not be count-sensitive.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:2:id: sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:5:tags: [session-log, user-correction, process-friction, context-checker-blind-spot, self-referential-gap, reading-order]
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:19:  - sig-2026-04-10-discuss-phase-authority-weighting-gap
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:32:    - "Session 09422ed4 L423 USER: 'have you indicated that reading order in the context'"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:38:    - "No plan artifact was written against the incomplete context"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:43:verification: {}
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:49:During Phase 57.4 planning context preparation, the orchestrator documented the authority-weighting lesson (deliberations > reference files) in STATE.md's Session Continuity and in the conversation itself, but did not place it in CONTEXT.md. The user caught this at session 09422ed4 L423 with a single question: "have you indicated that reading order in the context". The orchestrator acknowledged at L426: "No. I put the reading order in STATE.md Session Continuity and in my response to you, but not in CONTEXT.md itself. That is a gap — CONTEXT.md is what a fresh plan-phase session reads."
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:55:- Phase 57.4 planning context preparation (session 09422ed4)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:56:- Documents involved: STATE.md (Session Continuity section), CONTEXT.md (phase context document), and conversational response
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:57:- Gap: the authority-weighting lesson was placed in 2 of 3 relevant locations, missing CONTEXT.md
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:62:The orchestrator treated "documenting the lesson" as complete when the lesson was recorded in the most prominent status tracker (STATE.md) and in the conversational exchange with the user. But the most relevant audience for the lesson was a fresh plan-phase session reader, and that reader's primary context source is CONTEXT.md — not STATE.md's Session Continuity, not the conversation log.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:64:This is a specific instance of a more general pattern: orchestrators distinguish between "recorded" and "placed in the right location for the reader who needs it." Recording is necessary but not sufficient; placement is what closes the loop. The gap is self-referential in an instructive way: the lesson being documented was "the most recent deliberations should be weighted more heavily" (authority-weighting), and the gap was a failure to weight the most relevant location highly enough to put the lesson there.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-phase-574-context-md-missing-reading-order.md:66:This is `minor` because the recovery cycle was fast (user → orchestrator acknowledgment → fix, all in one session). But the self-referential nature is noteworthy: the orchestrator had just finished documenting a lesson about context-placement, and then failed to place that very lesson in context. This kind of gap suggests the orchestrator's context-placement reasoning is not recursive — it applies the lesson to future plans but not to the current session's own artifacts.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:2:id: sig-2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:8:  - capability-gap
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:9:  - verification
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:16:signal_type: capability-gap
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:35:1. **False factual claims:** The agent claimed "no workflow integration triggers lifecycle transitions" and "passive verification was never implemented." Both are false — execute-plan.md has an `update_resolved_signals` step and gsd-signal-synthesizer.md has passive verification logic (Step 4c). The claims were based on observing "0 remediated, 0 verified" in the KB and concluding "therefore no automation exists" without checking the codebase.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:43:The deliberation skill (`commands/gsd/deliberate.md`) has no epistemic verification step. After the Situation section is drafted with factual claims, nothing prompts verification against the codebase. The Evidence Base table tracks sources but does not distinguish "verified against code" from "inferred from observation." The skill also does not require checking prior deliberations before exploring the design space.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-deliberation-skill-lacks-epistemic-verification.md:51:This is the same class of failure as the signal lifecycle gap itself: the system designs epistemic safeguards (counter-evidence fields in signal schema, verification-by-absence in synthesizer) but doesn't apply those safeguards to its own deliberation process. The meta-system is not self-observing.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-orchestrator-skipped-log-sensor-despite-discovery.md:38:Phase 57 had a clean execution (10/10 verification, zero deviations in plans), so this is purely an orchestrator coordination gap, not a sensor or spec issue.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-plan-03-scope-extension-wiring-validation-undeclared.md:45:verification: {}
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-plan-03-scope-extension-wiring-validation-undeclared.md:67:1. **The test coupling is real.** The wiring-validation test is designed to enforce that every command with `execution_context` has a workflow @-reference. A new command without that reference necessarily requires either adding the reference OR adding an exception — and both options require test-file modification.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-pseudocode-template-var-wiring-test-failure.md:39:verification: "{}"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-test-count-exceeded-plan-target-phase38.md:33:verification: "{}"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-03-04-test-count-exceeded-plan-target-phase38.md:41:Plan 02 of phase 38 targeted 8-10 unit tests for the extensible sensor architecture. Execution delivered 11 unit tests -- slightly exceeding the target range. All tests passed with 10/10 verification.
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:9:tags: [upstream-adoption, verification-gap, discuss-phase, feature-drop, process-gap]
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:31:1. **Verification checked structure, not function.** The wholesale-replace of discuss-phase.md passed verification because the file grew from 408 to 1049 lines and gained codebase scouting. But the config routing that makes `discuss_mode: "assumptions"` work was in the *command file*, not the workflow file — and the entire alternative workflow + agent were separate files that were never created.
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:33:2. **A feature can be claimed adopted while its defining mechanism is absent.** The discuss-phase.md file was correctly updated with new capabilities (batch mode, analyze mode, text mode, advisor mode, KB scanning). But the `discuss_mode` config switch — the thing that routes to an entirely different workflow — was silently dropped. No test caught this because verification checked "does discuss-phase work?" not "does discuss_mode routing work?"
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:48:The verification must-haves likely checked "discuss-phase.md is updated" and "codebase scouting works" but had no must-have for "discuss_mode config routing works" or "assumptions workflow exists."
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:61:- Upstream adoption verification needs a "feature completeness" check, not just "file updated" checks
.planning/knowledge/signals/sig-2026-04-03-discuss-mode-adoption-gap-silent-feature-drop.md:63:- The `discuss_mode` feature should be properly adopted — it addresses a real need (codebase-first context gathering vs interview-style)
