.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:2:id: sig-2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:8:  - cap-enforcement
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:30:During Phase 57 signal collection, the synthesizer received 20 raw candidates from 4 sensors (artifact: 6, git: 1, ci: 4, log: 9). After dedup and trace filtering, 18 qualifying candidates remained. The per-phase cap (SGNL-09: max 10 signals per phase per project) forced the synthesizer to:
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:32:1. Archive 9 existing signals to restore cap compliance (phase 57 already had 18 active)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:38:- Worktree path resolution (resolveWorktreeRoot silent failure in worktree contexts)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:39:- Cross-runtime epistemic problems (agent findings accepted as authoritative without verification)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:41:- Multiple user-correction deviations (model mismatch, research ordering, context skipping)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:43:These are legitimate observations permanently lost to an arbitrary numeric cap.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:49:Phase 57 had 16 sessions spanning milestone research, 5 spikes, discuss-phase, plan-phase, and execution — far more workflow surface area than a typical 2-session execute-only phase. The cap treats all phases as equally complex, which they are not.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:55:The cap was set as a static numeric limit without considering:
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-per-phase-signal-cap-causes-information-loss.md:61:A better approach might be: no cap on detection/persistence, with triage (reflection) responsible for prioritization. Or a dynamic cap based on phase session count or sensor count.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-03-23-missing-home-for-constellation-recommendations.md:77:- adopted planning structure (`ROADMAP.md`, phases, context)
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-04-10-researcher-model-override-leak-third-occurrence.md:36:The feedback memory `feedback_model_override_scope.md` was created after the Phase 56 occurrence and explicitly says: "When user says 'use X for Y', only override the Y agent type. Check init JSON for each agent's configured model." Despite this memory existing and being loaded into context, the override still leaked.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/SIG-260222-005-zero-touch-manifest-architecture.md:27:Significantly reduces the cost of adding new features to GSD. Also reduces the risk of workflow drift — if feature logic is in one place (feature-manifest.json), it can't diverge between upgrade-project and new-project. The manifest becomes the canonical authority for "what does this feature look like".
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/sig-2026-03-19-qt31-source-namespace-pollution.md:59:2. **No CI check after commit**: The automation framework has signal collection as a postlude to phase execution, but quick tasks don't trigger CI verification. CI failures are only visible if someone checks.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-agent-used-upstream-gsd-tools-path-57-3.md:26:  - "archived by gsdr-signal-synthesizer at 2026-04-09T22:00:00Z: per-phase cap enforcement (phase 57 exceeded 10 signals)"
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-agent-used-upstream-gsd-tools-path-57-3.md:39:verification: {}
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-agent-used-upstream-gsd-tools-path-57-3.md:45:During phase 57.3, an agent repeatedly ran the upstream `$HOME/.claude/get-shit-done/bin/gsd-tools.cjs` path instead of the fork's installed `gsd-tools.cjs` path. Three correction messages were required before the agent used the correct path. This is related to the existing `sig-2026-04-09-skill-references-upstream-gsd-tools-path` signal which captures a structural version of this issue.
.planning/knowledge/signals/get-shit-done-reflect/2026-04-09-agent-used-upstream-gsd-tools-path-57-3.md:53:The agent's tool path resolution defaults to the upstream global installation, which is the more "obvious" path in the environment. The fork's installation path is less prominent and requires explicit knowledge of the dual-directory architecture. The skill spec files that reference the upstream path (captured in the related signal) contribute to this confusion by normalizing the wrong path in the agent's context.
